<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-23T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-23T05:00:00-05:00" n="179" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d179">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">123 [Hurley, Patrick J.]: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-23T17:00:00+07:00">November 23,
                                1944—5 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received November 24—8:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1890. Political Vice Minister<note n="26" xml:id="d179fn26">K. C. Wu.</note>
                        called me to Foreign Office this afternoon and made “oral statement” (of
                        which he handed me text) as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“President Roosevelt was reported to have stated in press conference
                                that he has selected the Ambassador to China and is asking for
                                agreement from China. In the meanwhile newspapers have prominently
                                mentioned Major General Patrick J. Hurley as the likely choice.</p>
                            <p>We have heard nothing officially and therefore desire to enquire
                                informally from the State Department if a decision has been made.
                                For your private information, General Hurley is entirely acceptable
                                to the Chinese Government.”</p>
                        </quote>
                    </p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>